title: Neurons that fire together, don't always wire together
body:
Neurons that fire together, don’t always wire together

As the adage goes ‘neurons that fire together, wire together,’ but a new article demonstrates that, in addition to response similarity, projection target also constrains local connectivity.

summary: Progressive overload in calorie deficit after years of daily alcohol? via /r/Fitness
title: Progressive overload in calorie deficit after years of daily alcohol? via /r/Fitness
body:
Hi all,

Been lifting fairly consistently for about 1.5 years and have seen some decent increases in my B/S/D.

During this entire time I’ve been a daily drinker, having at least 2-3 beers per day to wind down (I work a stressful job, and try to workout 4-6 days per week). I’ve always had an awkward skinny-fat beer gut body shape because of this. In the back of my mind, I always knew the calories from the booze was contributing. I wasn’t at a surplus, but was maintaining a slightly higher weight than I’m comfortable with.

Recently I decided enough was enough, and I was going to break the habit with a no-drink-November. I haven’t had a drink since Nov 1, and I’ve already dropped about 5 lbs.

If I’m adding weight to the bar while I’m in a deficit, does that mean that I will be losing muscle? How does it work if you’re in a deficit, but the weight on the bar, or your max reps at a certain weight continues to go up?

Once I get down another 15-20 lbs, I’ll probably start eating more (healthy) carbs to get back to maintenance / slight surplus.

summary: The Important Difference Between Sadness and Depression
title: The Important Difference Between Sadness and Depression
body:
The Important Difference Between Sadness and Depression

In my years of private practice, I’ve met many people struggling with depression who thought they were merely sad. I’ve also met many people who were extremely sad and worried they might be depressed. Because we associate depression with its primary symptom of pervasive sadness, many of us struggle to tell the difference between these two common psychological states.

This is a huge problem.

Our…
